props.text:
3298 years ago, a mega solar flare hit the Earth, rendering life on land impossible. Hence our ancestors moved deep underwater, an unfamiliar yet also the only livable place we left on Earth, naming the new city Hadal.

A smart AI system was developed over the years to maintain law and order amongst the citizens of Hadal. The AI eventually gained control over the system. With this, people lost the freedom of free thoughts, because the AI forbid certain ill thoughts such as aggression, theft and the abuse of drugs. The citizens of Hadal are monitored over “The Eyes” that the AI distributed all over Hadal. The Eyes are able to evaluate Hadian’s thoughts and emotions through brainwaves, converting them into cognitive values. These values then determine whether a person is a threat to society.

People who are identified as threats are expelled from Hadal. Robots that were developed and controlled by the AI act as enforcers of the system. They are deployed whenever a person is identified as a threat, escorting these threats to the ejection point known as “The Surface”. These “Threats” are given a final role of contributing to the expansion and development of Hadal by exploring the area around in a capsule. These capsules were specially designed to be able to withstand the immense pressure of the deep sea and provide a fixed amount of basic necessities such as oxygen and food that would slowly run out. These capsules also have The Eye to transmit data and information gathered back to the main system in Hadal.

In Hadal today, life is not that different from 3298 years ago, where a meritocratic system still exists, and Hadians are credited different societal status based on merit. 

A Hadian was detected as a threat after stumbling across an ancient book that contained contents about life 3298 years ago, where humans once lived on land. Hence, he was expelled from Hadal in the capsule. Knowing the fate that awaits him, he decided to find a way to this “life out of the sea” as he saw from the ancient book. And this is how he stumbled across the Museum of Memory.

In the Museum of Memory, he further learnt about what made mankind retreat into the deep sea, how the Museum of Memory was created by the people who chose to find a way to continue living on the land after the catastrophe and how it was built to educate Hadians in the event they resurface to the land.

In the year 3012, the remnants of humanity continue to struggle for survival, having endured the disastrous Great Flare that nearly wiped them out. The once vibrant and advanced civilizations have crumbled, leaving humans to navigate a world where nature has reclaimed its dominance. The idea of being the apex predator is a distant memory. Humanity now strives for survival against the fierce elements of the world.

Human lifespans are short, and memories of loved ones and happier times are fleeting. Despite this, people cling tenaciously to the past, desperate to remember a time when life was filled with joy, community, and harmony. This yearning drives them to scour the archipelagos, gathering relics and artifacts from the old world. These precious items are brought back to the Museum of Memories, a sanctuary dedicated to preserving human history.

In the Museum of Memories, these artifacts and their memory fragments are meticulously catalogued and uploaded into a vast databank. From this collection, a powerful simulation is born, offering an escape from the grim realities of the present and redirecting them to the endless virtual possibilities. Inside this virtual utopia, people can reunite with loved ones, forge new relationships, and create joyful memories.

Time flows differently in the simulation. What feels like hours or days inside can be mere minutes in the real world. This accelerated experience allows humans to live more fully within the digital realm than their shortened lifespans would permit in reality. For many, the simulation is a sanctuary, a place where they can find solace and happiness far removed from the hardships of their daily lives.

However, this escape is not without its critics. A growing faction believes that the simulation is a dangerous delusion, a blasphemy to the very essence of human existence. They argue that by rejecting the harshness of reality, people are turning their backs on the true struggles that define life. To them, embracing reality, no matter how painful, is the only way to find genuine meaning and purpose.

As humanity stands at this crossroads, they face a profound choice: to embrace real life, or to lose themselves in the comforting illusion of the past.

In 3012, humanity grapples with the aftermath of a catastrophic solar flare—the largest ever recorded. This event devastated our satellites, severing internet and communication services. As the Earth's damaged ozone layer failed to shield us from increased UV and IR radiation, temperatures soared, melting ice caps and elevating sea levels.

Adapting to these new conditions, humanity retreated to the ocean depths, forming a thriving underwater civilization shielded by water that mimics our former atmospheric protections - Aquatopolis. Utilising the kinetic energy of ocean currents and the abundant resources from seawater, such as salt, minerals, and silica, our society prioritises productivity and sustainability, powered by hydroelectricity and innovative extraction techniques. However, much has to be compromised to maintain this livelihood that we've developed.

Compulsory vocational training channels citizens into essential sectors like energy, manufacturing, and agriculture. Driven by a desperate need to survive, this was agreed upon by all to ensure that our civilization always has manpower present to produce essential resources. But we've learnt from experience - the status quo that we've built for ourselves could be swept away in an instant due to unpredictable natural phenomena. The Recon Corps was established to explore the world above the seabed, searching for new land. Their task of collecting information and data about the world beyond was seen as a safety measure for Aquatopolis - if our city begins to fail, we would hopefully know enough about the world beyond to relocate.

Equipped for this treacherous task, the Recon Corps utilizes advanced suits powered by solar energy. These suits protect against radiation and serve as mobile cartographic units. They collect, store and compare environmental data, display dynamic maps on their visors, and allow users to annotate and share discoveries. This technology fosters not just survival but a burgeoning curiosity about the surface world and potential human settlements beyond our aquatic enclave.

The Museum of Memories marks a milestone in the Recon Corps' progress. A satellite base was established by the Corps, having found land for the very first time. Initially intended to serve as a rest stop and cartographic database for explorers, missions on land have revealed a wealth of new information. Lifeforms never seen before, extreme fluctuations in temperature and radiation and interactions with terrain that would be impossible underwater. It quickly became a research centre aimed at familiarising the people of Aquatopolis - and anybody else who might reside underwater - with the world above. Utilising the base's ever-growing database, visitors can go through a series of simulations that emulate conditions on land at minimal risk to the visitor. We hope that one day, with the Museum of Memories serving as a launchpad, humanity will be able to explore the world above water once more and rediscover a home that had been lost to nature and time.
